<DOC><DOCNO> AP880627-0234 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 1524EDT</FILEID><FIRST>s p BC-Atlanta-At-A-Glance Adv03   06-27 0264</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Atlanta-At-A-Glance, Adv 03,0302</SECOND><NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3, and Thereafter</NOTE><HEAD>Convention '88</HEAD><HEAD>A Statistical Look At Atlanta</HEAD><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here are some facts and figures about Atlanta,home of the 1988 Democratic National Convention. Statistics are forthe metro area unless otherwise noted.</TEXT><BYLINE>THE CITY</BYLINE><TEXT>   City size: 136 square miles.   Counties in metro area: 18.   Metro area size: 5,147 square miles.</TEXT><BYLINE>THE PEOPLE</BYLINE><TEXT>   Population, city: 425,022, 1980 census.   Black population, city: 67 percent.   Population, 18-county metro area, 1980 census: 2,138,231.   Estimated population, metro, 1986: 2.5 million.   Black population, metro area: 25 percent.   Homeless population, city: 7,000-10,000, estimated.   Projected population, metro, year 2000: 3 million.   Median age, metro: 29 years.   ``Baby boomers'': 36 percent.   Atlanta natives: 41 percent.   Male-female ratio: 93-100.   Median education: 12.6 years.</TEXT><BYLINE>ECONOMICS AND BUSINESS</BYLINE><TEXT>   Average salary: $19,118.   Living below poverty level, city: 27.5 percent, 1980 census.   Typical metro home price: $110,333.   Largest employment sector, 1986: Service industries, 80 percent.   Largest employer, metro Atlanta: Delta Air Lines, 19,500.   Number of conventions, 1987: 1,617.   Convention attendance, 1987: 1.6 million.</TEXT><BYLINE>CLIMATE</BYLINE><TEXT>   Average high temperature, July: 87.   Record July high: 105.   Average low temperature, July: 69.   Record July low: 53.   Average rainfall, July: 4.9 inches.</TEXT><BYLINE>MISCELLANY</BYLINE><TEXT>   Number of Waffle House restaurants: 105.   Rafters, Chattahoochee River, average summer weekend: 16,500.   Professional sports championships: One, 1968 Atlanta Chiefs,soccer.   Smallest Atlanta Braves baseball crowd: 737, Sept. 8, 1975, vs.Houston.   Original city name: Terminus.   Number of streets somehow named ``Peachtree'': at least 34.   Height of IBM Tower, city's tallest building: 825 feet.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE></DOC>